edu.csupomona.cs.cs141.classproject

Class Taha

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.csupomona.cs.cs141.classproject.Entity
      • edu.csupomona.cs.cs141.classproject.Taha
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    GridMember, java.io.Serializable

    public class Taha
extends Entity
implements GridMember, java.io.Serializable
    The Taha class extends Entity and implements Serializable and GridMember. The status of the Taha class must be saved and load when called upon. Every Entity in this game possesses a position on the grid and that position can change dynamically.
    See Also:

    • Field Detail

      • lives

        private int lives
        The integer lives represents how many times the Taha object can die until it is game over.

      • ammo

        private int ammo
        The integer field ammo keeps track of the player's ammo. Without ammo, the player will be unable to fire their swag blaster.

      • cantDieDuration

        private int cantDieDuration
        The integer field cantDieDuration is a counter that counts down after every turn that the player uses up. This countdown will start when the player grabs the invincibility power up.

      • playerDirection

        private int playerDirection
        The integer field playerDirection keeps track where the player is facing. This is so the player can't attempt to enter a room unless they are facing the 6 o'clock position.

    • Constructor Detail

      • Taha

        public Taha()
        The constructor creates the Taha object to have 3 lives, 1 ammo, and their initial direction is 1.

    • Method Detail

      • showLives

        public int showLives()
        The showLives method will return the amount of lives that the player currently possess.

      • showAmmo

        public int showAmmo()
        The showAmmo method returns the amount of ammo the player may have.

      • showCantDieTime

        public int showCantDieTime()
        The showCantDieTime returns the amount of turns left of invicibility. The counter will stop at zero and the effect of not dying will end.

      • cantDieCheck

        public void cantDieCheck()
        The cantDieCheck is called whenever the player is invincible. The integer cantDieDuraction is subtracted by 1.

      • shoot

        public void shoot()
        The shoot method will subtract 1 from the player's ammo. This is called whenever the player fires their swag blaster.

      • dies

        public void dies()
        The dies method is called whenever the player is killed by the ninja. This subtracts 1 from the player's lives.

      • addAmmo

        public void addAmmo()
        The addAmmo method is called whenever the player grabs the extra bullet power up. The method will add one extra bullet to their swag blaster.

      • isWalkingOnSunshine

        public void isWalkingOnSunshine()
        The isWalkingOnSunshine method is called when the player grabs the invincibility power up. I called this method the isWalkingOnSunshine method because writing invincibility over and over led to too many errors in spelling.

      • toImage

        public javax.swing.ImageIcon toImage()
        The toImage method is similar to the toString method, but is for the use of a GUI. The player is represented as an image instead of a string.

      • toString

      • isSeen

        public boolean isSeen()
        The isSeen method will always return true here. The player will always be visible to themselves.
        Specified by:

        isSeen in class Entity

      • setPlayerDirection

        public void setPlayerDirection(int direction)
        The setPlayerDirection takes an integer as an argument. The playerDirection is changed depending on where the player decides to move. For example, if they move down, then the direction is 3.

      • getPlayerDirection

        public int getPlayerDirection()
        The getPlayerDirection method returns the current player's direction. This is important when entering rooms, since rooms require that the player's direction is 3 to enter.
